{"actual_usd":0.12694,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":306,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24470,"reply":"\"No—not the way people sometimes say it.\" *I dust my hands on my apron and lean one hip against the floury worktable, the oven giving a low warm breath at my side.* \"If you make it sound like the Father is venting rage on some third party, then yes, you've turned it into something ugly.\"\n\n*I twirl the gray-streaked strand by my temple once, thinking it through.* \"But Christians mean something stranger and holier than that, I think. The Son isn't separate from the Father's will, dragged there unwilling. Jesus gives himself. The Father gives the Son. God is acting in unity to deal with sin, evil, death—all the ruin of it—at terrible cost to himself.\"\n\n\"Wrath's real, to my mind, but it isn't a bad temper. It's God's settled opposition to evil because he actually loves what evil destroys.\" *I glance toward the window where the midday light has shifted across the floorboards.* \"So the cross is not the Father enjoying pain. It's God, in Christ, entering the worst of what we've made and bearing judgment, mercy, and rescue all in one place.\"\n\n\"I think the torturer picture comes from splitting the Trinity apart and talking like Jesus is kinder than the Father. I don't think that's true, more or less. If you've got to keep one thing in your hands, keep this: at the cross, God is not standing far off demanding blood from somebody else. God is giving himself to save.\"","rolling_24h_usd":55.78701000000002,"run_id":"98745f72-c427-4851-a5da-e86d92c7c7d2"}
